      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA366-kiḷavi">iḵtulakiyaṟ kūṟip poruḷvayiṉ piriya valitta neñciṟkut talaimakaṉ colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what HE said to the heart that covetted separating for the sake of wealth, talking about the way of the world.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA366">
<l>            aravukkiḷarn taṉṉa viravuṟu palkāḻ</l>
<l>            vīṭuṟu nuṇṭuki lūṭuvan timaikkun</l>
<l>            tiruntiḻai yalkuṟ peruntōṭ kuṟumakaṇ</l>
<l>            maṇiyē raimpāṉ mācaṟak kaḻīik</l>
<l>            kūtir mullaik kuṟuṅkā lalari</l>
<l>            mātar vaṇṭoṭu curumpupaṭa muṭitta</l>
<l>            virumpaṉ mellaṇai yoḻiyak karumpiṉ</l>
<l>            vēlpōl veṇmukai viriyat tīṇṭi</l>
<l>            mutukkuṟai kurīi muyaṉṟucey kuṭampai</l>
<l>            mūṅki laṅkaḻait tūṅka voṟṟum</l>
<l>            vaṭapula vāṭaikkup pirivōr</l>
<l>            maṭavar vāḻiyiv vulakat tāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Those who separate for the north wind from the northern fields,</l>
<l rend="indent">	that presses, so that the pretty shafts of the bamboo sway,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	on the nests made with effort by the birds ripe in wisdom(?),</l>
<l rend="indent">	seizing to unfold them the lance-like white buds of the sugar-cane,</l>
<l rend="indent">	while the bed of dark many soft [tresses]<note place="foot">Syntax is a little puzzling here, and the main information is (for a change) elliptical here, but the attributes (<term xml:lang="ta">irum pal meṉ</term>) make it quite clear that the bed consists of HER hair, as is the topos. Perhaps it is best to take <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟumakaḷ</term> as subject of <term xml:lang="ta">muṭitta</term> and coordinate the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻīi</term>.</note> stays behind,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	that are washed spotlessly in five sapphire-like parts</l>
<l rend="indent2">	[and] complemented, for bees with beautiful bees to come,<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">curumpu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">vaṇṭu</term>, connected by a sociative particle, obviously refer to two different species of insects, presumably two varieties of bees.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">	with short-stemmed blossoms of jasmine of the cool season,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	by the little woman with big shoulders [and] hips with perfect jewels,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	where, when the gliding fine cloth comes down from [her] waist,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	many mixed pearl-strings glitter, like a snake emerging,<note place="foot">Is this an early reference to cobra hoods and <term xml:lang="ta">alkul</term>? But here the <term xml:lang="ta">kāḻ</term> seems to be compared to the snake.</note></l>
<l>they are ignorant, live, in this world.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
